Arrays allows us to store multiple values of the same data type

eg,

int[] marks = {12, 45 , 78};

to traverse thro, we can use for loops like we normally do

    for(int mark:marks)
    {
        System.out.println(mark);
    }

but we generally use, 

    ==>     int[] marks = new int[5];

we can individually acces the values with index
==>     marks[0] = 12
        marks[2] = 78

length of arrays can be found by, 

    marks.length
    [no brackets]

we can also make arrays of classes

class person
{
    ......
}

person people = new person[5];

we cannot print an array just like that, we have to use

    System.out.println(marks)   ---------------> X
    System.out.println(Arrays.toString(marks)); --------> correct

to initate all the values in an array, 
    Arrays.fill(marks,100);         ==> {100,100,100,100,100
    }

to check if 2 arrays are equal, we can use

Arrays.equal(array1,array2);

we can also sort arrays, by using

Arrays.sort(array1);

 